    "When gradually reducing T i, the 90 degree phase advance of C(jω) will unavoidably confront a phase drop of G(jω) at some unknown but higher frequency ω > ω c pi.",
    "Note that the drop can be smaller, e.g.",
    "-90 deg per decade, or larger, e.g.",
    "-180 or -270 deg per decade, depending on the locus of dominant poles of G(s).",
    "Worth case, an even larger phase drop can appear in case of a dominant time delay."
  ],
